180":"1099年–1180年","1026–Male":"1026年–歿","–Female":"歿","1115":"1115年","1026":"1026年","1099":"1099年","1087":"1087年","1040":"1040年","1180":"1180年","Alwington, Devon, , England":"英國英格蘭戴文阿爾文頓","Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France":"法國諾門迪卡爾瓦多斯凱","lifeSummary":"Sir Jean Ricardus Chauvin是Jean Nicholas Chauvin和Desert Francoise的兒子，於1040年出生在法國諾門迪卡爾瓦多斯凱。他至少有1個兒子。他去世於1115年在英國英格蘭戴文阿爾文頓享年75歲。"},"zh-hans":{"1040–1115":"1040年–1115年","1040–1087":"1040年–1087年","1099–1180":"1099年–1180年","1026–Male":"1026年–殁","–Female":"殁","1115":"1115年","1026":"1026年","1099":"1099年","1087":"1087年","1040":"1040年","1180":"1180年","Alwington, Devon, , England":"英国英格兰戴文阿爾文頓","Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France":"法国諾門迪卡爾瓦多斯凱","lifeSummary":"Sir Jean Ricardus Chauvin是Jean Nicholas Chauvin和Desert Francoise的儿子，于1040年出生在法国諾門迪卡爾瓦多斯凱。他至少有1个儿子。他去世于1115年在英国英格兰戴文阿爾文頓享年75岁。"},"hr":{"1040–1115":"1040.–1115.","1040–1087":"1040.–1087","1099–1180":"1099–1180","1026–Male":"1026–preminuo","–Female":"preminula","1115":"1115.","1026":"1026","1099":"1099","1087":"1087","1040":"1040.","1180":"1180","Alwington, Devon, , England":"Alwington, Devon, Engleska, United Kingdom","Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Caen, Calvados, Normandie, Francuska"},"cs":{"1040–1115":"1040–1115","1040–1087":"1040–1087","1099–1180":"1099–1180","1026–Male":"1026–Zesnulý","–Female":"Zesnulá","1115":"1115","1026":"1026","1099":"1099","1087":"1087","1040":"1040","1180":"1180","Alwington, Devon, , England":"Alwington, Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom","Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Caen, Calvados, Normandie, Francie"},"da":{"1040–1115":"1040–1115","1040–1087":"1040–1087","1099–1180":"1099–1180","1026–Male":"1026–Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1115":"1115","1026":"1026","1099":"1099","1087":"1087","1040":"1040","1180":"1180","Alwington, Devon, , England":"Alwington, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Caen, Calvados, Normandie, Frankrig"},"nl":{"1040–1115":"1040–1115","1040–1087":"1040–1087","1099–1180":"1099–1180","1026–Male":"1026–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1115":"1115","1026":"1026","1099":"1099","1087":"1087","1040":"1040","1180":"1180","Alwington, Devon, , England":"Alwington, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Caen, Calvados, Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1040–1115":"1040–1115","1040–1087":"1040–1087","1099–1180":"1099–1180","1026–Male":"1026–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1115":"1115","1026":"1026","1099":"1099","1087":"1087","1040":"1040","1180":"1180","Alwington, Devon, , England":"Alwington, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chauvin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Marcel, Michel, Anatole, Camille, Emile, Lucien, Raoul, Amedee, Angelle, Dany.","French: nickname derived from <i>chauve</i> ‘bald’ (from Old French <i>chauf</i>, Latin <i>calvus</i>). Compare   Shovan   and   Shover  .","History: Jean Chauvin from Fresquienne in Seine-Maritime, France, married Marie-Madeleine Courtois in Boucherville, QC, in 1702. His descendants also bear the surname   Charleville  . — Another Chauvin family, from Anjou, represented by ‘Grand’ Pierre Chauvin, was in Montreal, QC, by 1653. Three of his sons were with Jean-Baptiste Le Moyne, Sieur de Bienville, in Biloxi in 1700, and a fourth joined them in 1706. They settled in New Orleans, where their descendants achieved great prominence. — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"Cauvin","meanings":["French: nickname derived from <i>cauve</i>, a regional form of <i>chauve</i> ‘bald’ (see   Chauvin  ). Compare   Covin  ."]},{"name":"Shovan","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Chauvin  ."]},{"name":"Charleville","meanings":["French: habitational name from Charleville, the name of several places in the northern part of France. This surname is virtually non-existing in France.","History: In North America, this surname was originally a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne by Joseph Chauvin <i>dit</i> Charleville (a grandson of Jean Chauvin from France; see   Chauvin  ), who married Marie-Geneviève-Monique Rivard in Kaskaskia, IL in 1740."]},{"name":"Chavana","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Humberto, Justo, Rosalinda, Ruben, Adan, Adela, Ademar, Adolfo, Concha, Eladia, Erasmo, Ernestina.","Hispanic (Mexico): of French origin, reportedly an altered form of <b>Chauvain</b>, itself a variant of   Chauvin  . Alternatively, perhaps from a rare variant of   Chavanne  ."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"Jean","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Like   Jane   and   Joan  , a medieval variant of Old French <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Towards the end of the Middle Ages this form became largely confined to Scotland. In the 20th century it became more widely used in the English-speaking world and enjoyed a period of great popularity, but it is now out of fashion. Among numerous well-known and influential bearers are the British novelists  Jean Plaidy  (  Eleanor Hibbert ,  1910–93 ) and  Jean Rhys  (  Ella Gwendolen Rees Williams ,  1894–1979 ), British actress  Jean Simmons  (  1929–2010 ), and American-born actress  Jean Seberg  (  1938–79 ). It is also found as a variant spelling of the masculine name   Gene ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]},{"name":"Jeane","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jean ."]}]},{"name":"Ricardus","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Rickards  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rickards","meanings":["English (West Midlands): variant of   Rickard  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. Compare   Richards  , with which it was often interchangeable."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Jean Ricardus Chauvin was born in 1040, in Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France as the son of Jean Nicholas Chauvin and Desert Francoise. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1115, in Alwington, Devon, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1040–1115":"1040–1115","1040–1087":"1040–1087","1099–1180":"1099–1180","1026–Male":"1026–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1115":"1115","1026":"1026","1099":"1099","1087":"1087","1040":"1040","1180":"1180","Alwington, Devon, , England":"Alwington, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Caen, Calvados, Normandie, P